Guy Charles Clark (November 6, 1941 – May 17, 2016) was an American folk and country singer-songwriter and luthier.
Clark was born in Monahans, Texas.
His family moved to Rockport, Texas in 1954.
After he graduated from high school in 1960, Guy spent almost a decade living in Houston as part of the folk music revival in that city.
and he eventually settled in Nashville, where he helped create the Americana music genre.
His songs "L.A. Freeway" and "Desperados Waiting for a Train" helped launch his career and were covered by numerous performers, including Steve Earle and Brian Joens.

On his passing, the New York Times described him as "a king of the Texas troubadours", declaring his body of work "as indelible as that of anyone working in the Americana idiom in the last decades of the 20th century".
